<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-03-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="888" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d888">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Sickles</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-03-21"><hi rend="italic">March 21,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 427.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of Mr.
                            Storer’s No. 642, of the 3d instant, reporting the position assumed by
                            the Spanish authorities in the case of Antonio Gisbert y Bayot.</p>
                        <p>In reply I have to say that the Department is of opinion that it is
                            perhaps not unreasonable for those authorities to require Mr. Gisbert to
                            show the place of his residence on April 11, 1899, the date of the
                            exchange of ratifications of the treaty of peace.</p>
                        <p>As his mother has gone to Manila to obtain the necessary evidence, no
                            further action seems to be required at this time.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>